#week-title("Two", "The Seven Planetary Rulers")

=== Core Teaching

From the understanding of natural interconnection flows the *Doctrine of
Correspondences*: planets rule plants as their higher archetypes govern their lower
expressions. Each of the seven classical planets imparts its characteristic virtue
to the plants under its domain.

- *The Sun* rules St. John’s Wort and Rosemary.
- *The Moon* rules Jasmine and Melissa.
- *Mars* rules Nettles and Garlic.
- *Venus* rules Rose and Mint.
- *Mercury* rules Lavender and Dill.
- *Jupiter* rules Agrimony and Sage.
- *Saturn* rules Comfrey and Horsetail.

=== Topics This Week

- The seven classical planets as archetypal forces
- Representative plants for each planetary ruler
- Introduction to the chain of correspondences: metals, planets, and plants

#inner-work[
  *Introducing the Tarot*

  The Tarot is the symbolic record of the Great Work encoded in images. It is
  introduced here not as fortune-telling, but as a living book of correspondences
  — a set of pictorial keys in which the same forces you are working with in the
  laboratory are given visible form.

  *First Tarot Practice:*
  Separate the 22 Major Arcana from the rest of the deck. Lay them in numerical
  order and look at them. Without reference to any book, divide them into three
  groups based on your own observation:
  1. Cards depicting stages of human development.
  2. Cards depicting forces acting on events.
  3. Cards depicting powers affecting all living things.

  Record your groupings in a separate *Tarot Journal*.
]

